frameDefinitions: The words in this frame describe situations in which a Perpetrator carries off and holds the Victim against his or her will by force. '' 'Two men kidnapped a Millwall soccer club employee, police said last night.'

The words in this frame describe situations in which the Perpetrator secretly takes Goods into or out of a country or other area which are prohibited by law or on which one has not paid the required duty.
These are words describing situations in which a Perpetrator takes Goods from a  Victim or a Source.
An Agent begins preventing a Captive from moving despite a tendency or desire on the part of the Captive to do so.
An Agent removes a Theme from a Source so that the it is in the Agent's possession.
frameExamples: Two men <t>kidnapped</t> a Millwall soccer club employee, police said last night.
I can't believe he <t>pickpocketed</t> my gold watch !
Authorities recently <t>captured</t> several suspects who were hiding in a remote mountain area.
Milton <t>took</t> the can of beer out of the refrigerator.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Perpetrator</fen> is the person (or other agent) who carries off and holds the <fen>Victim</fen> against his or her will.
The <fen>Victim</fen> is the person who is carried off and held against his/her will.
When the kidnapping occurs.
Where the kidnapping takes place.
This is the person (or other agent) that illegally takes the goods into or out of a country.
The role Goods is anything (including labor, time, or legal rights) that can be illegally taken into our out of a country.
The source is the location the goods occupy initially before change of location.
The path refers to (a part of the) ground the Goods travel over or to a landmark the Goods travel by.
Goal is the location the Goods end up in.
When the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.
<fen>Perpetrator</fen> is the person (or other agent) that takes the goods away.
<fen>Victim</fen> is the person (or other sentient being or group) that owns the goods before they are taken away by the perpetrator.
<fen>Goods</fen> is anything (including labor, time, or legal rights) that can be taken away.
<fen>Source</fen> is the initial location of the goods, before they change location.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the theft occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the theft occurs.
The entity which is captured.
The <fen>Agent</fen> brings the <fen>Captive</fen> into custody.
The <fen>Cause</fen> is the non-sentient entity which is responsible for restricting the movement or location of the <fen>Captive</fen>.
When the event occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the event occurs.
The person who takes possession of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The <fen>Agent</fen> takes possession of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The location of the <fen>Theme</fen> prior to the taking.
When the taking takes place.
Where the taking takes place.
